# CASE 3: AGE
# -----------------------------
```{r}
library(readxl)
#Age is also strongly associated with household income. Median household income generally rises with age through prime working years, peaks among households aged 45 to 54, and then declines in older age groups. This pattern reflects the typical life-cycle of earnings, where income increases with labor market experience and career advancement before falling as households approach retirement.

#Among all age groups, households aged 45 to 54 were the most financially advantaged, reporting the highest median income. Younger households, especially those aged 15 to 24, earned substantially less, reflecting lower labor force attachment and earlier career stages. Income also declines among households aged 65 and older, which is consistent with retirement and reduced wage income.

#Several age groups experienced statistically meaningful changes between 2023 and 2024, particularly those aged 15 to 24, 35 to 44, and 45 to 54. This suggests that income changes in 2024 were not the same as some working-age groups seeing more measurable shifts than others.
# Census Excel file
url <- "https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/demo/tables/p60/286/tableA1.xlsx"

# Download to temporary local file
tmp <- tempfile(fileext = ".xlsx")
download.file(url, destfile = tmp, mode = "wb")

# Read downloaded Excel file
ageRaw <- read_excel(tmp, sheet = 1)

# Clean column names manually
ageIncome <- ageRaw |>
  rename(
    age_group = 1,
    households_2023 = 2,
    median_2023 = 3,
    moe_2023 = 4,
    households_2024 = 5,
    median_2024 = 6,
    moe_2024 = 7,
    pct_change = 8,
    pct_change_moe = 9
  )

# Keep only age rows
ageIncome <- ageIncome |>
  filter(age_group %in% c(
    "Under 65 years",
    "15 to 24 years",
    "25 to 34 years",
    "35 to 44 years",
    "45 to 54 years",
    "55 to 64 years",
    "65 years and older"
  ))

# Remove aggregate row
ageIncome <- ageIncome |>
  filter(age_group != "Under 65 years")

# Add significance flag
ageIncome <- ageIncome |>
  mutate(
    significant_change = age_group %in% c(
      "15 to 24 years",
      "35 to 44 years",
      "45 to 54 years"
    ),
    pct_change = readr::parse_number(as.character(pct_change))
  )

print(ageIncome)
```
